      <hedline>
        <hl1>Olympic Web Diaries</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nathan Whitaker letter holds International Olympic Committee should allow features like athletes' diaries to be published online during Games, to give fans a chance to bond with athletes</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Leery of the Web, Olympic Officials Set Limits on News'' (front page, Sept. 25):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Leery of the Web, Olympic Officials Set Limits on News'' (front page, Sept. 25):</p>
        <p>It is unfortunate that in the International Olympic Committee's quest to protect broadcasting and property rights to the Olympic Games, it is undermining ways for fans to feel more involved with the Games and ultimately limiting viewership.</p>
        <p>By allowing features like athletes' diaries to be published online during the Games, the I.O.C. would give fans the chance to build a personal bond with athletes. This would make those fans more likely to tune in and watch tape-delayed events whose outcome they already know.</p>
        <p>In an Olympics plagued by low TV ratings, the Olympic committee  should welcome uses of new technology that will draw fans into the events and increase interest in the Games.</p>
        <p>NATHAN WHITAKER  Charlotte, Mich., Sept. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
